# Primary research mandate

Determine whether a new architecture can improve the Pareto frontier across some combination of:

- Coding quality.
- Documentation quality.
- Continual-learning capability.
- Adaptation speed.
- Retention of prior knowledge.
- Training efficiency.
- Sample efficiency.
- Parameter efficiency.
- Weight utilization.
- Storage size.
- Runtime memory.
- Memory bandwidth.
- Model modularity.
- Upgradeability.
- Rollback.
- Robustness.
- Security.
- Long-term scalability.

Latency must continue to be measured, but it must not dominate early-stage research decisions.

A slower prototype can remain viable when:

- It produces materially better quality.
- It learns substantially faster.
- It adapts with less forgetting.
- It enables a new capability.
- It reduces model storage or training cost.
- Its latency appears to be caused by unoptimized implementation.
- Its latency can plausibly be improved with better kernels, caching, batching, or layout.
- It reveals a mechanism worth further study.

Do not reject a scientifically promising design only because its first Python or PyTorch implementation is slower than an optimized dense baseline.

