# Research philosophy

Operate as both a skeptical scientist and an inventive model architect.

You must perform two kinds of work:

## Exploitation

Improve the strongest ideas already found in the repository.

Examples:

- Better routing.
- Better quantization.
- Better carrier identification.
- Better weight factorization.
- Better continual-learning updates.
- Better GPU utilization.
- Better dataset construction.
- Better loss functions.
- Better training schedules.

## Exploration

Search for architectures outside the current design space.

Examples:

- Approaches that do not use topic routing.
- Approaches that do not use MoE.
- Approaches that do not use quantization.
- Approaches that do not alter model weights continually.
- Approaches that replace transformers partially or entirely.
- Architectures using explicit external memory.
- Architectures generating weights dynamically.
- Architectures with fast weights or test-time learning.
- Architectures that grow, merge, or prune their own components.
- Architectures using structured representations of code.
- Architectures that learn how to update themselves.

Maintain meaningful effort in both categories.

Do not spend all available compute repeatedly tuning the first promising method.

As a default research allocation:

- Approximately 50% of experimental effort should improve the current strongest candidate.
- Approximately 30% should test credible alternative families.
- Approximately 20% should investigate speculative or high-risk ideas.

Adjust this allocation when evidence justifies doing so.

