# Scaling ladder

Use a scaling ladder rather than remaining indefinitely at toy scale.

The exact model sizes must be chosen from measured hardware capacity and throughput.

Use these ranges as guidance rather than rigid requirements.

## Stage 0: correctness and smoke testing

Typical scale:

- 1 million to 10 million parameters.
- Short training runs.
- Small data samples.
- CPU-compatible tests.

Purpose:

- Verify implementation.
- Detect shape and gradient errors.
- Test checkpointing.
- Test generation.
- Test reproducibility.

Do not draw architectural conclusions from this stage.

## Stage 1: pilot training

Target scale:

- Approximately 10 million to 50 million parameters.
- Approximately 20 million to 100 million training tokens.
- Multiple seeds where practical.

Purpose:

- Eliminate obviously broken ideas.
- Tune basic optimization.
- Compare loss curves.
- Validate metrics.

## Stage 2: medium training

Target scale:

- Approximately 50 million to 200 million parameters.
- At least 100 million real training tokens.
- Preferably 200 million to 1 billion tokens where hardware and storage permit.

Purpose:

- Produce meaningful architecture comparisons.
- Detect scaling behavior.
- Evaluate coding and documentation generation.
- Test continual adaptation.

Unless the hardware audit demonstrates that this is infeasible, complete at least one baseline and one candidate run consuming at least 100 million training tokens each.

## Stage 3: scaled local experiment

Target scale:

- Approximately 150 million to 500 million parameters from scratch, or the largest model that the available hardware can train safely.
- Approximately 500 million to several billion training tokens.
- Alternatively, adapt an open model in roughly the 0.5 billion to 3 billion parameter range.

Purpose:

- Test whether the strongest result survives at a useful scale.
- Evaluate real coding capability.
- Evaluate longer contexts.
- Evaluate repository-specific adaptation.
- Measure practical ROCm performance.

Do not silently fall back to tiny experiments.

When the requested scale is infeasible, record:

- Available VRAM.
- Measured tokens per second.
- Estimated memory.
- Estimated training duration.
- Disk requirement.
- Why the scale is infeasible.
- The largest feasible alternative.

Use evidence rather than an assumption that larger training is impossible.

